text: Part of effective horror is taking a comforting cultural touchstone and twisting it into something recognizable but grotesque. They are also heavily relying on the James Gunn producer credit, but James Gunn is only one out of eight producers for this movie. text: One thing I noticed in the Trailer, the scene when the kid was levitating above the open door to his ship in the barn he crashed landed in was putting off a Red glow, Interesting note is from the 1978 Superman Clark Kent in the middle of the night goes out to the barn due to something calling out to him in the space ship, he wonders out to the barn in the middle of the night same senario and then stumbles upon something putting of a Green glow, he then finds a Green crystal....Now in this trailer Brandon Breyer is drawn to the ship in the same way,  late at night, and once the doors were opened to his ship, a red glow emerges, *Red Crystal hint?* There is enough differences to note here and call backs to the older superman films to make me hypothesize this will indeed be a 2nd child who made it off the planet Crypton just like Clark kent, and this being the story of this child, one who chose the dark side of life instead of Superman's virtuous one. Shrugs thinking to much into it? let me know what you all think!! Also if you want to see the scene i am referring to, just youtube Clark Kent finds on the farm crystal | Superman, weird sentence but its the best version of this scene on youtube.

text: I encourage no one to endorse this film, perverting the idea of Superman, making him a monster before he becomes a good person...human as it is, right now we need less human and more human idealism. Your leaders propagate fear and now your entertainment takes a bright light of hope and darkens it for a dollar. Taking no consideration of the influence this will have on the population in its current soft and fearful state. Some may say its just a movies, but those smart enough to understand the human mind, we know that the writing of super heroes and villains can play a large part in peoples perspectives on life. Do not let the entertainment business kill what made Superman human. He grew up with compassion for those who could not otherwise save, or defend themselves from greater evils. He did not rampage and kill because he didn't understand who he was. His parents saw to him understanding that he was different the responsibility it meant and they set him on a path that made him more human than humanity itself. Superman is a portrayal of the best of us and how alien that can be in a world filled with fear and evil intent. Sony pictures is going to far, and if you have any humanity left in you, do not go see this film. Stand with Superman as a world community, I ask you please send Sony and this director a message. We will not let you make monsters of our heroes. We will not endorse your greed at the expense of our humanity. Boycott this film please, for the love of humanity.

text: Guys i have a theory. In the trailer the mother says: "dave is in the barn, it was like he was DRAWN to it". The barn is where they keep the ship the boy crash landed in. I think that maybe the boy is the last living of another species that was sent to earth to destroy it and "re-colonize" it for his original species. Plus in this trailer we see that the kid eats a fork and in the 2nd trailer we see he's immune to metal(metal cant damage him) when he stops the blade of the lawnmower with his fingers. So my theory is that his species couldnt adapt to earth's resources and stuff like that so they sent him to adapt to it and then destroy all humans for the new species to arrive. The ship is supposed to somehow "activate" some kind of protocol in his brain that makes him highly aggressive to everyone he sees and the "protocol" is turned off when he completes it.

So with him gaining these new powers was did scare him like the scene with the fork. Now as we all know from superman green kryptonite weakens him physically but the  Red kryptonite effect the emotional state, making him angry and evil. So if the red glow was the Red kryptonite then that could explain him turning evil and being picked on doesn't help. Now with that mark it looks extremly close to the berserk mark, now for all of those who don't know berserk's mark is the brand of sacrifice, now the brand sacrificed, someone close and important to the summoner, are then offered to creatures of the darkness. so cause the kid was exposed to the red glow and if it is going to be based on superman then he was drawn to it and it was causeing him to suffer emotionaly, so thats where the brand could come in. to sacificed someone close to the summoner and the summon could be the boy offers his mother. I'M not sure about the father. Now of course we all know if you mess with the darkness and offer them something they will take over your body so the kid could be prossed and been devourd by a demon. text: LOL if anyone notice the subtle hidden message in this movie??? I'm not trying to trash this movie or trash anyone or whoever it may triggered. Well, to point it out clearly to whoever miss it if anyone really miss it.... Now let me explain. First to compare a similar movie, the superman... In this version it was the lady who taught the "alien boy/Superboy" human western's moral concept. While in Superman version, it was Clark adopted dad who adopt him who taught "alien boy/ Clark" human western's moral concept. Now if you had watch the trailer for this movie, with the concept being taught by the lady in this movie. she taught the boy that he was a gift, point out that he was different without any child reinforce to assure the child who suffering identity crisis to be strong, and she even rub the ego about how the kid was special. Okay so, if in real life you overpraise a kid like the same way like this lady in this trailer did, obviously you'll create a monster who think he is special, who above other, had a unique gift who no on in the world could go against him. You'll create a antithesis hero. Now, let compare how clark fair in his world. He got a supporting dad like this lady in this video. But, the main thing that is different is the way how Clark dad taught him moral ideology to support him to be a man who should learn to take responsibility for his action. In conclusion if you still don't understand. This movie is pointing out that in the case of Women Vs Man moral teaching to a hero, thing sure take a wrong turn. I haven't watch the movie yet but just based in the trailer, this is how the trailer transcribe in a weird sense to me.

text: I haven't seen the movie, but I heard that this is sort of "What if Superman was evil, right from the beginning?"  Newsflash: Superman wouldn't be like this, because Superman has abilities that this kid doesn't -- super vision (at an atomic level), and super hearing (not just across the street thing, but all over the world).  And above all else, Superman has the ability to break the planet with a single punch (and that's his low-balling his powers).  To him, killing people is so unbelievably beneath him.  Lex explained it in Superman All Star, when Lex had Superman's powers for few minutes.  He understood that with Superman's powers, you would have no choice but to be altruistic.  Of course, this Kal is inexperienced, and his powers are clearly VERY underdeveloped, so I suppose it's possible for him to go nuts at this stage of his life.
